Jeff Wicks, News24 (iStock) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cape Town - A Plettenberg Bay man has recounted the moment a shark tore into his surf-ski, flinging him into the water on Friday.- Read more: Plett paddler in brush with sharkNSRI spokesperson Craig Lambinon said rescue volunteers had been notified of the shark encounter shortly after 08:00.&ldquo;Five men, all locals from Plettenberg Bay, reported that while paddling on a regular paddle one of the surf-skis had been pushed from behind violently, causing the paddler, Dave Manson, to be thrown out of the surf-ski,&rdquo; he said.Speaking to News24, Manson said he was taken completely by surprise.&ldquo;He hit me from behind and I didn&rsquo;t even see the shark,&rdquo; he said.&ldquo;I would like to try and take this out of my mind,&rdquo; he added.Manson said that the shark had torn into the rear of the paddle-ski, ripping about 12 inches (30cm) off the back near the skegs.&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t feel like I had a brush with death. I don&rsquo;t want to sound overly casual about it but I was taken by surprise. It pushed the boat up and then I fell into the water.&rdquo;He said that even while in the water, he didn&rsquo;t feel overly threatened.&ldquo;There was a swirl in the water and even when I was in the water I didn&rsquo;t feel like I was in too much danger. "The guys I was paddling with just enclosed around me so if the shark was going to take me it would have had to have done so from right underneath. Then I just lay on another guy&rsquo;s boat and he paddled me in,&rdquo; he said.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.